PART 6: BAER SUBPLANES IN PG(2,q) AND TOURNAMENT SHADOWS
======================================================================

  PG(2,q) parameters:
    q=2: 7 points, 7 lines, 3 points/line
    q=3: 13 points, 13 lines, 4 points/line
    q=4: 21 points, 21 lines, 5 points/line
    q=5: 31 points, 31 lines, 6 points/line
    q=7: 57 points, 57 lines, 8 points/line
    q=8: 73 points, 73 lines, 9 points/line
    q=9: 91 points, 91 lines, 10 points/line

  Baer subplane PG(2,q) inside PG(2,q^2):
    q=2: PG(2,4) has 21 pts, Baer sub has 7 pts (0.3333), 7 Baer lines, 14 secant-1 lines
    q=3: PG(2,9) has 91 pts, Baer sub has 13 pts (0.1429), 13 Baer lines, 78 secant-1 lines
    q=4: PG(2,16) has 273 pts, Baer sub has 21 pts (0.0769), 21 Baer lines, 252 secant-1 lines
    q=5: PG(2,25) has 651 pts, Baer sub has 31 pts (0.0476), 31 Baer lines, 620 secant-1 lines

  TOURNAMENT CONNECTION:
  At q=2: PG(2,4) has 21 points. PG(2,2) = Fano plane has 7 points.
  21 = C(7,2) = number of arcs in a 7-tournament!
  7 = number of vertices = number of Fano points!

  The Fano plane PG(2,2) as a Baer subplane of PG(2,4):
  - 7 points of the Fano plane sit inside the 21-point plane
  - The 7 lines of the Fano (each with 3 points) become
    'Baer lines' in PG(2,4)
  - The remaining 21 - 7 = 14 points are 'external'

  In tournament terms:
  - The 7 vertices of T_7 are the Fano points
  - The 21 arcs of T_7 are the PG(2,4) points
  - Each Fano line (3 points) corresponds to a TRIANGLE
  - The 7 Fano lines = 7 special triangles

  The Paley tournament on 7 vertices IS the Fano geometry:
  QR(7) = {1, 2, 4} (quadratic residues mod 7)
  The Fano lines are {0,1,3}, {1,2,4}, {2,3,5}, {3,4,6},
                     {4,5,0}, {5,6,1}, {6,0,2}
  Each is a translate of {0,1,3} mod 7.

  Paley tournament T_7 (QR = {1,2,4}):
  3-cycles: 14, transitive triples: 21
  Total triples: 35 = C(7,3) = 35
  3-cycle fraction: 14/35 = 0.4000
  H(Paley_7) = 189
  Mean(H) at n=7 = 78.75 = 78.8

======================================================================
PART 7: CONE ITERATION -- TOWER OF CONES
======================================================================

  Cone tower: starting from the 3-cycle C_3 (H=3):
  C_3 has H = 3 on 3 vertices
  Cone(C_3) has H = 3 on 4 vertices
  Cone^2(C_3) has H = 3 on 5 vertices
  Cone^k(C_3) has H = 3 on 3+k vertices

  So H=3 is achieved at EVERY n >= 3.
  Similarly, H=1 (transitive tournament) is achieved at every n >= 1.

  Starting from T_3 (transitive, H=1):
  Cone(T_3) has H = 1 on 4 vertices
  This is the transitive T_4 (or one of its relabelings)

  H-spectra (all achieved values) for n=3..6:
  n=3: |Spec| = 2, values = [1, 3]
  n=4: |Spec| = 3, values = [1, 3, 5]
        Values from n=3 that appear (via coning): [1, 3]
        NEW values at n=4: [5]
  n=5: |Spec| = 7, values = [1, 3, 5, 9, 11, 13, 15]
        Values from n=4 that appear (via coning): [1, 3, 5]
        NEW values at n=5: [9, 11, 13, 15]
  n=6: |Spec| = 19, values = [1, 3, 5, 9, 11, 13, 15, 17, 19, 23, 25, 27, 29, 31, 33, 37, 41, 43, 45]
        Values from n=5 that appear (via coning): [1, 3, 5, 9, 11, 13, 15]
        NEW values at n=6: [17, 19, 23, 25, 27, 29, 31, 33, 37, 41, 43, 45]

======================================================================
PART 8: 6-FOLD SYMMETRY AND THE HEXAGONAL STRUCTURE
======================================================================

  S_3 (symmetric group on triangle) has order 6.
  Elements: {e, r, r^2, s, sr, sr^2}
  This is the SAME 6 as pi(4) = 6.

  In tournament terms:
  - A triangle (3 vertices) has S_3 symmetry
  - The Fibonacci parity mod 4 has period 6
  - The 6-fold return IS the S_3 action on the basic triangle

  More precisely: the Fibonacci matrix F = [[0,1],[1,1]]
  acts on (Z/4Z)^2 with order 6.
  The group <F> mod 4 is isomorphic to Z/6Z.
  And Z/6Z = Z/2Z x Z/3Z (Chinese Remainder Theorem).
  The Z/2Z factor is the 'edge flip' (complement)
  The Z/3Z factor is the 'triangle rotation'
  Together: the 6-fold period encodes edge-flip x triangle-rotation!

